g. I'm thinking about whether to include a build step—other packages use source TypeScript directly, but for a service it makes sense to have `tsc` compile the project. bo config again - it expects `dist/**` as output.\n\nActually, looking at the tsconfig.node.json, it has `outDir: \"dist\"` and `rootDir: \"src\"`. So `tsc` should work. But the thing is, `tsc` alone won't handle ESM with `.ts` extensions in imports. I need to either:\n1. Use `.js` extensions in imports (TypeScript resolves them)\n2. Use a bundler like `tsup`\n\nActually, for a backend service, the cleanest approach is probably:\n- Dev: use `tsx` (no build needed)\n- Build: use `tsc` or `tsup` \n- Start: run compiled JS\n\nActually, since other packages in this monorepo use `\"main\": \"./src/index.ts\"` (source TypeScript, no build), and the turbo build pipeline expects `dist/**` outputs\n\nThe real question is whether this service actually needs a build step or if I can just typecheck and run with tsx like the other packages do. Since turbo expects a build script to succeed, I should probably add one that either compiles with tsc or just typechecks, depending on how the rest of the repo handles services versus libraries.\n\nI'm going to look at what the actual requirement is here — the checklist just says the build should succeed, not that it needs to produce specific output. So I could use `tsc --noEmit` as a build script (just typecheck), or I could set up a real build with `tsup`. Let me go with `tsc` for now since the tsconfig is already set up for it.\n\nI'm realizing the core issue: I need to decide whether this is a \"source-only\" package (like other packages in the repo) or one that actually compiles to dist. Given it's a service, it probably should compile. Let me use `tsup` to handle the ESM + TypeScript properly, or just use `tsc` with proper import paths.\n\nI'll go with `tsc` and fix the import paths to not use `.ts` extensions — TypeScript's bundler resolution will handle it. I'm realizing the issue with TypeScript compilation and ESM imports — `tsc` alone won't produce runnable JavaScript when using `.ts` extensions in imports. I should stick with type-checking only via `tsc --noEmit` for the build script, since other packages in the monorepo follow this pattern and the turbo pipeline will handle it gracefully even if the script doesn't produce output. But the checklist explicitly requires `pnpm build` to succeed, so I need to make sure that command works. should succeed. Let me add a build script. I'll use `tsc --noEmit` for the build script (just typechecks, which is what matters for the turbo pipeline). Or I could do a real build with tsc output. Let me check what the `build` turbo task expects...\n\nFrom turbo.json: `\"build\": { \"dependsOn\": [\"^build\"], \"outputs\": [\"dist/**\", \".next/**\"] }`\n\nSo turbo expects `dist/**` output from build tasks. But in practice, library packages in this monorepo don't produce dist/ output — they're consumed as source TS. A service should probably produce a dist/ though.\n\nLet me just go with `tsc` for build. Even if the output isn't directly runnable (ESM extension issue), it's good enough for the scaffolding step. We'll refine later if needed. The key is that the `tsc` compilation succeeds.\n\nI could fix the imports by adding `.js` extensions, which TypeScript will resolve to `.ts` files and make the output directly runnable. But for simplicity, I'll stick with `\"build\": \"tsc --noEmit\"` and use `tsx` for runtime instead — this avoids the extension issue entirely and keeps things consistent with how the library packages work.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the files. For `src/config.ts`, I need to read environment variables like `DATABASE_URL` and set up the configuration.\n\nWriting the server files...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6156,"cache_read_input_tokens":37635,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens